 

Here’s the exact step-by-step you can follow 👇
________________________________________
✅ Step 1 — Load Your Tables
1.	Open Power BI Desktop
2.	Click Home → Get Data
3.	Load your tables (Excel / CSV / Database)
Example tables:
•	Customers
•	Orders
•	Products
•	Payments
Once loaded → you already have the “entities” of ER diagram.
________________________________________
✅ Step 2 — Go to Model View (This is your ER Diagram)
On the left side, click the Model icon (3rd icon).
🎯 This screen = ER Diagram automatically generated
Each table = Entity
Each column = Attributes
________________________________________
✅ Step 3 — Create Relationships (This draws the ER lines)
If Power BI didn’t auto-create:
1.	Drag CustomerID from Customers → drop on Orders.CustomerID
2.	Drag ProductID from Products → Orders.ProductID
3.	Drag OrderID from Orders → Payments.OrderID
Now you will see lines between tables.
These lines are your relationships in ER diagram.
________________________________________
✅ Step 4 — Set Cardinality (Very Important for ER)
Double click the relationship line.
Set:
Relationship	Cardinality	Meaning
Customers → Orders	One to Many (1:*)	One customer, many orders
Products → Orders	One to Many (1:*)	One product, many orders
Orders → Payments	One to One (1:1) or 1:*	Depends
Click OK
Now your ER diagram is logically correct.
________________________________________
✅ Step 5 — Arrange Tables like ER Diagram
You can drag tables and arrange like this:
Customers    Products
      \      /
        Orders
          |
       Payments
This becomes your schema mockup.
________________________________________
✅ Step 6 — Hide Unnecessary Columns (to look like clean ER)
Right click column → Hide in report view
Keep only:
•	Primary keys
•	Foreign keys
•	Important fields
Now it looks exactly like a professional ER diagram.
________________________________________
✅ Step 7 — Rename Tables & Columns (Schema Style)
Rename like database schema:
•	tbl_Customers
•	tbl_Orders
•	tbl_Products
Rename columns:
•	Customer_ID
•	Order_ID
•	Product_ID
Now it looks like database schema mockup.
________________________________________
✅ Step 8 — Screenshot / Export for Documentation
This Model view = your ER diagram.
Take screenshot and use in:
•	Documentation
•	PPT
•	Project report
•	Training material



✅ Aim
To design and visualize an Entity-Relationship (ER) diagram and schema mockup by importing multiple related tables from Excel into Power BI and creating relationships using the Model View.
________________________________________
✅ Algorithm
1.	Prepare an Excel file containing multiple related tables such as Customers, Products, Orders, and Payments with proper primary and foreign keys.
2.	Open Power BI Desktop and select Home → Get Data → Excel to import the prepared Excel file.
3.	Load all the sheets (tables) into Power BI Data Model.
4.	After loading, navigate to the Model View to visualize the tables as entities.
5.	Identify the Primary Keys in each table (Customer_ID, Product_ID, Order_ID, Payment_ID).
6.	Identify the Foreign Keys used to connect the tables (Customer_ID in Orders, Product_ID in Orders, Order_ID in Payments).
7.	Create relationships by dragging the foreign key column from one table to the corresponding primary key column in another table.
8.	Set the cardinality of relationships appropriately (One-to-Many between Customers and Orders, Products and Orders, Orders and Payments).
9.	Arrange the tables properly in the Model View to resemble a clear ER diagram structure.
10.	Hide unnecessary columns and keep only important keys and attributes to make the schema clean and readable.
11.	Rename tables and columns, if required, to follow proper database schema naming conventions.
12.	Save the Power BI file and capture the Model View as the final ER diagram and schema mockup for documentation.

